<img src="http://ia.imdb.com/media/imdb/01/I/40/73/31m.jpg" align="left"> 

<table width="250">
<tr>
<td bgcolor="#F8F3D7">
<font size="2" face="arial">IMDB: <a href="" target="new"></a><br>
Buy this here: <a href="" target="new">Buy!</a><BR></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
<font size="2" face="arial"> M. Night Shyamalan takes a crack at comedy... I think<br><br>I saw this movie in theatres, but it didn't really warrant a review at the time. However, with release on DVD imminent, I figure a warning is in order before anyone goes out and buys this thing:<br />
<br />
This movie must be the first by Shyamalan (Sixth Sense, Unbreakable) that doesn't involve Bruce Willis. <br />
<br />
That said, Signs is one of the greatest comedies I've seen in a long time. I haven't laughed so much in a movie theatre in years. I don't get why everyone else was so silent and jumpy.. I guess they just didn't get the masterful and intentional hijinks of Mel Gibson playing a Priest/Farmer. I sure laughed more during this film than during Mr. Deeds.<br />
<br />
It's good to see Shyamalan branching out from his usual genre of mildly creepy movies with a depressed lead male character and an obnoxiously cute child following him around.<br />
<br />
In this film, Mel Gibson plays an incredibly depressed priest who's wife got run over by the director, Shyamalan himself, with his brother, a depressed ex-baseball player who couldn't hit the broad side of a barn, being followed around by two obnoxiously cute childeren. <br />
<br />
Entire party gets mildly creeped out after various symbols appear in their fields. Hilarity ensues as the situation goes from mildly creepy to downright ridiculous, ending in a final climax that reveals the point of the story, and was suitibly sappy.<br />
<br />
Not only does the director/writer/God with a funky name which I keep having to cut and paste to ensure I spell it right decide to star in his own film, but he picks the guy who killed Gibson's wife, causing most of the story's plot developping moments in the form of flashbacks, but his character happens to know exactly what's going on and where to go to be safe.<br />
<br />
This does provide one absolutely hilarious scene, that had me laughing obnoxiously loud. When you first see the director's character, everyone is out sitting down at a table when he drives by. Every main character turns to stare at him in reverence, and one of the childeren whispers to the other, "Is that him?" and the other nods. Recognizing him immediately as the director, I seriously thought this was some sort of unrelated-to-the-story yet incredibly clever joke. Instead it turned out to be them just mildly creeped out by the guy who bisected Gibson's wife with a pickup and a well placed tree.<br />
<br />
Final Verdict: The movie does actually try to be serious and funny at the same time, with a definite leaning on the serious. But there were too many unplanned ridiculous moments to pull off the right vibe, in my case, anyways. (By the way, in case you can't tell who the director is in the movie, he'll be the only Indian looking guy in a hick town of all white people.)<br />
<br />
The movie is pretty good, worth a rental at least, and has the signature Shyamalan style of pulling seemingly unrelated things together in the last few scenes (In fact, that's the point of the whole damn movie.)<br />
<br />
Some people may even manage to be creeped out by it if you turn the lights out and make scary noises at them. Even then, they deserve a smack or two.</font></div>
</tr>
</div>
